      "\n   We need to prove this inequality, given the available hypotheses.\n\n3. **Key Observations**:\n   - The terms `|RiemannSum (f n) a b M - ℓ n|` and `|RiemannSum (f m) a b M - ℓ m|` are less than `ε / 4` by `hM1` and `hM2`, respectively.\n   - The other two terms are also bounded by `ε / 4` by `hNn` and `hNm`.\n   - The inequality looks like it is trying to bound `|ℓ m - ℓ n|` by the sum of these four terms, but currently it is not clear how the four terms relate to `ℓ m` and `ℓ n`.\n\n4. **Potential Misunderstanding in Proof Sketch**:\n   - The actual goal in the Lean code is to show that the sequence `ℓ` is Cauchy, and this step is part of that proof. However, the current approach seems to involve bounding `|ℓ m - ℓ n|` using differences of Riemann sums, but the chosen bound appears arbitrary and not directly useful. The actual plan (not reflected in this snippet) would likely be to use the fact that the differences of integrals can be bounded using the uniform convergence of `f n` to `F` and the fact that the Riemann sums for `f n` approximate `ℓ n`, etc. But in the current Lean snippet, the `b1` statement seems to be trying to combine these terms without a clear plan. \n   - A better approach might be to recognize that the sum of the four terms is `≥ |ℓ m - ℓ n|`, but the current inequality is not obvious. Alternatively, perhaps we need a different way to relate these terms.\n   - A more careful analysis of the Riemann sums and the assumed bounds might be required.\n\nBut since we are only asked to replace the `sorry`, perhaps it is just a matter of proving the inequality as stated, regardless of whether the approach is correct or not.\n\n#### Examining the Inequality\nLooking at the inequality:\n```\n|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |R (n) - ℓ n| + |R (n) - R (F)| + |R (m) - R (F)| + |R (m) - ℓ m|\n```\nBut `R (F)` here is `RiemannSum F a b M`.\n\nThis looks like it can be derived using the triangle inequality if we expand `ℓ m - ℓ n` in terms of the Riemann sums. \n\nHere’s a possible derivation:\n\n1. Write `ℓ m - ℓ n = (ℓ m - R (m)) + (R (m) - R (F)) + (R (F) - R (n)) + (R (n) - ℓ n)`.\n2. Then take absolute values and apply the triangle inequality:\n   `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R (m)| + |R (m) - R (F)| + |R (F) - R (n)| + |R (n) - ℓ n|`.\n3. Since `|R (F) - R (n)| = |R (n) - R (F)|`, the inequality is equivalent to what is needed, except that the Lean statement has `R (m) - R (F)` and `R (n) - R (F)` instead of `R (F) - R (m)` and `R (F) - R (n)`.\n\nBut in Lean, the statement is:\n```\n|R (n) - ℓ n| + |R (n) - R (F)| + |R (m) - R (F)| + |R (m) - ℓ m|\n```\nThis is actually the same as \n```\n|R (n) - ℓ n| + |R (m) - ℓ m| + |R (n) - R (F)| + |R (m) - R (F)|\n```\nwhile the intended bound was \n```\n|ℓ m - R (m)| + |ℓ n - R (n)| + |R (n) - R (F)| + |R (m) - R (F)|.\n```\nBut note that `|ℓ m - R (m)| = |R (m) - ℓ m|`. So the Lean inequality is correct, because it is exactly the same as:\n`|ℓ m - R (m)| + |ℓ n - R (n)| + |R (n) - R (F)| + |R (m) - R (F)|`.\n\nTherefore, we can use the first step:\n`ℓ m - ℓ n = (ℓ m - R (m)) + (R (m) - R (F)) + (R (F) - R (n)) + (R (n) - ℓ n)` to get the required inequality.\n\n### Proof Sketch\n\n1. Expand `ℓ m - ℓ n` as `(ℓ m - R_m) + (R_m - R_F) + (R_F - R_n) + (R_n - ℓ n)` where `R_i` are the Riemann sums. \n2. Take absolute values and apply the triangle inequality:\n   `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_F - R_n| + |R_n - ℓ n|`.\n3. Since `|R_F - R_n| = |R_n - R_F|`, we can rearrange the terms to get the required form.\n\nBut in Lean, `ℓ m` is `ℓ m`, and `R_m` is `RiemannSum (f m) a b M`. The Lean inequality is:\n```\n|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |R_n - ℓ n| + |R_n - R_F| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_m - ℓ m|\n```\nBut we have:\n`|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_F - R_n| + |R_n - ℓ n|`\nBut since `|R_F - R_n| = |R_n - R_F|`, we can write the right-hand side as `(|R_n - ℓ n| + |ℓ m - R_m|) + (|R_n - R_F| + |R_m - R_F|)`.\n\nBut Lean requires us to prove:\n`|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |R_n - ℓ n| + |R_n - R_F| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_m - ℓ m|`\nwhich is exactly the same as above because `|ℓ m - R_m| = |R_m - ℓ m|` and we can reorder the summation.\n\n### Formal Proof Steps\n\nWe will:\n1. Rewrite `ℓ m - ℓ n` as a sum of four terms.\n2. Use the triangle inequality to bound its absolute value by the sum of the absolute values of the four terms.\n3. Recognize that this gives exactly the right-hand side of the required inequality.\n\n### Lean Code Adjustments\n\nIn Lean, we can directly prove the inequality by using the following steps:\n1. Note that `ℓ m - ℓ n = (ℓ m - R_m) + (R_m - R_F) + (R_F - R_n) + (R_n - ℓ n)`.\n   - This is easily checked by algebra.\n2. Take the absolute value of both sides and apply the triangle inequality.\n3. Observe that `|(R_F - R_n)| = |(R_n - R_F)|` and similarly for other terms.\n4. The result follows by rearranging the sum.\n\nBut in Lean, we cannot directly write this because we would need to keep track of the intermediate terms like `R_F - R_n`. Alternatively, we could just directly apply the triangle inequality multiple times:\n```\n|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - ℓ n|\n```\nand then break down `|R_m - ℓ n|` further.\n\nBut perhaps the easiest way is to write:\n```\n|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_F - R_n| + |R_n - ℓ n|\n```\nand then recognize that this is the same as the RHS in the goal (because of absolute value symmetries).\n\nTo do this in Lean:\n- Use `abs_sub_le` repeatedly to get:\n  - `|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - ℓ n|`\n  - `|R_m - ℓ n| ≤ |R_m - R_F| + |R_F - ℓ n|`\n  - etc.\nBut perhaps it’s easier to instead add `(ℓ m - R_m)` and `(R_m - ℓ n)` etc.:\n\nAlternatively, note that:\n```\nℓ m - ℓ n = (ℓ m - R_m) + (R_m - R_F) + (R_F - R_n) + (R_n - ℓ n)\n```\nand thus \n```\n|ℓ m - ℓ n| ≤ |ℓ m - R_m| + |R_m - R_F| + |R_F - R_n| + |R_n - ℓ n|.\n```\n\nThis is straightforward because:\n```\nabs (x + y + z + w) ≤ abs x + abs y + abs z + abs w.\n```\n\nIn Lean, this is derived from `abs_add` applied repeatedly:\n```\nabs (x + y + z + w) ≤ abs (x + y + z) + abs w\nabs (x + y + z) ≤ abs (x + y) + abs z\nabs (x + y) ≤ abs x + abs y\n```\nSo we can use `abs_add` multiple times.\n\nBut instead of writing it out, perhaps we can use the fact that for any `x y z w : ℝ`, `abs (x + y + z + w) ≤ abs x + abs y + abs z + abs w`. This would directly give the inequality if we set:\n- `x = (ℓ m - R_m)`\n- `y = (R_m - R_F)`\n- `z = (R_F - R_n)`\n- `w = (R_n - ℓ n)`\n\nBut this requires proving a general version of `abs (x + y + z + w) ≤ abs x + abs y + abs z + abs w`, which we can easily do by applying `abs_add` three times.\n\nBut we also note that Lean’s `abs_add` is `abs (a + b) ≤ abs a + abs b`, so we can use it to write:\n```\nabs (a + b + c + d) ≤ abs (a + b + c) + abs d ≤ abs (a + b) + abs c + abs d ≤ abs a + abs b + abs c + abs d\n```\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the following is better:\n```\nabs (a + b + c + d) = abs ((a + b) + (c + d)) ≤ abs (a + b) + abs (c + d) ≤ (abs a + abs b) + (abs c + abs d)\n```\n\nBut perhaps the most straightforward way is to use `abs_add` repeatedly:\n```\nabs (a + b + c + d) ≤ abs (a + b + c) + abs d ≤ abs (a + b) + abs c + abs d ≤ abs a + abs b + abs c + abs d\n```\n\n### Final Proof Strategy\n\n1. First, show that `ℓ m - ℓ n` can be written as `(ℓ m - R_m) + (R_m - R_F) + (R_F - R_n) + (R_n - ℓ n)` (algebra).\n2. Then, take the absolute value and use the triangle inequality to get `abs (ℓ m - ℓ n) ≤ abs (ℓ m - R_m) + abs (R_m - R_F) + abs (R_F - R_n) + abs (R_n - ℓ n)`.\n3. But `abs (R_F - R_n) = abs (R_n - R_F)` and similarly `abs (ℓ m - R_m) = abs (R_m - ℓ m)` and `abs (R_n - ℓ n) = abs (ℓ n - R_n)` (but we don't need this last one).\n   - Actually, in Lean",
